sentence-detokenized: FOOTBALL - JAPAN WINS HAPPILY, CHINA SUFFERS A SURPRISE DEFEAT.
Japan began their defence of the Asian title with a 2-1 win over Syria in the Group C championship match on Friday.
But China saw their luck run out in the second game of the group, surprisingly losing 2-0 to newcomers Uzbekistan.

China controlled most of the game and missed several chances until the 78th minute, when Uzbek striker Igor Shkvyrin took advantage of a misdirected defensive header to lob the ball over the advancing Chinese goalkeeper and into an empty net.
Oleg Shatskiku secured the win in injury time with an unstoppable left-footed shot from outside the box.
The former Soviet republic was participating in the Asian Cup finals for the first time.
Despite winning the Asian Games title two years ago, Uzbekistan is an underdog in the final.
Two goals from defensive errors in the last six minutes allowed Japan to come from behind and take all three points from their opening game against Syria.

Takuya Takagi scored the winner in the 88th minute, rising to head Hiroshige Yanagimoto's cross towards the Syrian goal, which goalkeeper Salem Bitar appeared to have covered, but then let slip into the net.
It was Syria's second costly mistake in four minutes.
Defender Hassan Abbas rose to intercept a long ball in the box in the 84th minute, but only managed to deflect it into the top corner of Bitar's goal.
Nader Jokhadar had given Syria the lead with a well placed header in the seventh minute.
Japan then laid siege to the Syrian penalty area for most of the game, but rarely broke through the Syrian defence.
Bitar made great saves every time they did it.
Japanese coach Shu Kamo said: "Syria's own goal brought us luck.
The Syrians scored early and then played defensively and adopted long balls, which made it difficult for us. '
Japan, co-hosts of the 2002 World Cup and ranked 20th in the world by FIFA, are the favourites to reclaim their title here.
Hosts the United Arab Emirates play Kuwait and South Korea face Indonesia on Saturday in Group A matches.
All four teams are tied on one point each after one match.

FOOTBALL - LATE GOALS GIVE JAPAN A WIN OVER SYRIA.
Two goals in the last six minutes gave defending champions Japan a 2-1 Asian Cup win over Syria on Friday.
Takuya Takagi headed home the winner in the 88th minute of this Group C match after goalkeeper Salem Bitar spoiled a clean sheet by letting the ball go under his body.
It was the second Syrian defensive error in four minutes.
Defender Hassan Abbas rose to intercept a long ball in the box in the 84th minute, but only managed to deflect it into the top corner of Bitar's goal.
Syria had taken the lead with their first serious attack in the seventh minute.
Nader Jokhadar directed Ammar Awad's cross from the right into the top right corner of Kenichi Shimokawa's goal.
Japan then laid siege to the Syrian penalty area and were denied a goal for offside in the 16th minute.
A minute later Bitar made a double save, first from a Kazuyoshi Miura header and then from a Takagi shot.
In the 37th minute, Bitar again saved Miura's header from a corner.
Japan started the second half brightly, but Bitar denied them an equaliser when he dived to his right to stop Naoki Soma's low shot in the 53rd minute.

FOOTBALL - THE BAN ON INDICATORS IS LIFTED.
Dutch striker Reggie Blinker had his indefinite suspension lifted by FIFA on Friday and was due to make his return to Sheffield Wednesday against Liverpool on Saturday.
Blinker has missed his club's last two matches after FIFA handed him a worldwide ban for appearing to sign contracts for Wednesday and Udinese while playing for Feyenoord.
The FIFA Players' Status Committee, meeting in Barcelona, decided that, although Udinese's document was basically valid, it could not be legally protected.
The committee said that the Italian club had violated the rules by not informing Feyenoord, with whom the player was under contract.
Blinker was fined 75,000 Swiss francs ($57,600) for failing to inform the English club of his previous involvement with Udinese.
FOOTBALL - LEEDS 'BOWYER FINED FOR FAST FOOD FIGHT
Leeds' England Under-21 striker Lee Bowyer was fined £4,500 ($7,400) on Friday for throwing chairs at restaurant staff during a disturbance at a McDonald's fast food restaurant.
Bowyer, 19, who was caught on security cameras, pleaded guilty to a charge of affray at a London court.
He was fined and ordered to pay a total of £175 to two staff members injured in the fight at an east London restaurant in October.
Leeds had already fined Bowyer £4,000 ($6,600) and warned that a repeat of his criminal behaviour could cost him his place in the team.
Bowyer, who joined the Yorkshire club in August for £3.5m ($5.8m), was due to play against Middlesbrough on Saturday.

RUGBY UNION - CAMPESE'S FAREWELL LITTLE REGRETTED.
Centre Jason Little will miss Australia's end-of-tour match against the Barbarians at Twickenham on Saturday.
Little chose not to risk aggravating the knee injury that has kept him out of much of the tour and is replaced by fellow Queenslander Daniel Herbert.
Owen Finegan has recovered from the knocks he took in last weekend's Test against Wales and retains his place in the backline ahead of Daniel Manu.

The Wallabies are aiming for a thirteenth consecutive win to end their European tour with a 100 per cent record, but they are also looking to go all out and give David Campese a proper send-off in his final game for Australia.
The Wallabies are not currently planning a special presentation to the 34-year-old winger, but the 75,000-strong crowd will still gather in the hope of witnessing one last moment of magic.
Campese will face a familiar opponent in Barbarians captain Rob Andrew, the man who led Australia to defeat with a last-minute goal in the World Cup quarter-final in Cape Town.
"Campo is very popular in this country and the fans have always followed him since he first played here in 1984," said Andrew, who is likely to make his last appearance at Twickenham.
On tour, Australia won all four Tests against Italy, Scotland, Ireland and Wales, scoring 414 points, an average of almost 35 points per game.

League obligations have limited the Barbarians' selection options, but they still have 13 internationals, including England back Tim Stimpson and recalled winger Tony Underwood, as well as All Black forwards Ian Jones and Norm Hewitt.

FOOTBALL - UNCAPPED PLAYERS TO FACE MACEDONIA
Romania coach Anghel Iordanescu on Friday called up three players who were not included in his squad to face Macedonia next week in a World Cup qualifier.

Midfielder Valentin Stefan and striker Viorel Ion of Otelul Galati and defender Liviu Ciobotariu of National Bucharest are the newcomers for the European group eight clash in Macedonia on 14 December.
Iordanescu said he chose them because of their good performances in the national championship in which National Bucharest is leading and Otelul Galati third. "
I think it is right to give them a chance," he told reporters.
Defending champions Steaua Bucharest, who finished bottom of their Champions League group in the European Cup, have only two players in their squad.
Attacking midfielder Adrian Ilie, who recently left Steaua for Turkish club Galatasaray, was sent off after receiving two yellow cards.

CRICKET - LARA ENDURES ANOTHER MISERABLE DAY.
Australia gave Brian Lara another reason to be unhappy when they beat West Indies by five wickets in the opening match of the World Series limited overs on Friday.
Lara, who was sanctioned for misconduct on Wednesday, was sent off for five points, continuing a string of disappointing results on tour.
Australia, who hold a 2-0 lead in the five-Test series, surpassed West Indies' total of 172 with eight balls to spare to end a run of six consecutive one-day defeats.
All-rounder Greg Blewett led his team to a comfortable victory with a record 57 in 90 balls, much to the delight of the 42,442 spectators.
Man-of-the-match Blewett came into the wicket with the total on 70 for two and made three quads in an innings of 129 minutes.
His crucial fifth-wicket partnership with fellow countryman Stuart Law, who scored 21 runs, added 71 runs in 85 balls.
Lara looked out of sorts during his brief stay on the field before taking a simple catch from Shane Warne at mid-off.
West Indies tour director Clive Lloyd apologised for Lara's behaviour on Tuesday.
He (Lara) had told Australian coach Geoff Marsh that wicketkeeper Ian Healy was not welcome in the visitors' dressing room.
The Melbourne crowd were clearly furious at the incident, jeering loudly at the West Indies vice-captain as he made his way to midfield.
It was his fellow left-hander Shivnarine Chanderpaul who held on with a brave 54, despite being hampered by a groin injury.
Chanderpaul was forced to rely on a runner for most of his innings after he was injured while rushing back to his seat to avoid being out.
Pakistan, who arrive in Australia at the end of the month, are the other team competing in the World Series tournament.

CRICKET - LARA SUFFERS ANOTHER MISERY FROM THE AUSTRALIAN TOUR.

West Indies batsman Brian Lara suffered another blow on his Australian tour, having already been sanctioned for misconduct, when he was rudely dismissed in the first match of limited overs against Australia on Friday.
Lara, who received a severe reprimand from his own management after a tantrum with Australian keeper Ian Healy, scored five goals to extend a run of poor batting.
The West Indies vice-captain struggled to find his rhythm during his 36 minutes in the field, before sending a Tom Moody ball straight to Shane Warne at midwicket.
West Indies were 53 for two in 15 overs when rain stopped play at the Melbourne Cricket Ground after skipper Courtney Walsh won the toss and elected to bat.
Lara's outburst three days ago clearly turned some of the Australian public against him.
As he made his way to the ticket office, he was greeted by loud boos from some of the crowd.
Several times during his innings, the crowd joined in a series of obscene chants against him.

Tour manager Clive Lloyd apologised on Wednesday for Lara's behaviour in confronting Australian coach Geoff Marsh in the opposition dressing room to protest against his dismissal in the second Test on Tuesday.
Lloyd did not specify what form the discipline would take.
Lara, who holds the record for the highest score in Test cricket and first class, was unhappy with Healy's role in the incident and wondered if the ball had hit the Australian keeper.
Australia went on to win the match at the Sydney Cricket Ground by 124 runs to take a two-nil lead in the five-Test series after Lara failed to score in both innings.
Lara has yet to score a century since the West Indies arrived in Australia five weeks ago.
Officials from the Caribbean and Australian teams played down the incident, stressing that relations between the two teams had not been affected.
Pakistan, who arrive next week, are the third team in the World Series triangular tournament.
